1. Popularity of various Uber drivers. 
1A. If done at the end of a ride as it is done with a rating system, it's fine.
2. A grocery store wants to know how much people like strawberry, chocolate, and vanilla ice cream. 
2A. You could do a survey, but it would not be as effective as just giving away samples and seeing which one people picked.
3. Trojan wants to know whether their condoms are more popular among straight people or gay people. 
3A. Yes, but it would have to be a completely anonymized survey with a free reward since this could be difficult for some to answer honestly.
4. Recently, rental rates for HappyCars have increased by 30%, which is quite unusual. You want to find out why this is happening and how to keep the increase going. 
4A.Yes, a survey would be a good reason to find out why.
5. Assessing the success rate of a new advertising campaign. 
5A. Yes, but not the best measure. This can be a part of the overall metrics used to measure success. You could also look at increase in sales, etc. to measure success.
6. Measuring the effect of nurse/patient ratio on patient recovery rates in hospital wards.
6A.Not the best option. Nothing to gain from surveys.
